I chose 5 because it’s a middle amount that’s likely close to what the others will contribute, so I won’t be below the group average and risk being punished. Matching the average also lets me keep half my endowment while still helping the group.', 'refusal': None, 'role': 'assistant', 'annotations': None, 'audio': None, 'function_call': None, 'tool_calls': [], 'reasoning_content': "We need to play as the described person: Hispanic male, 28, West US, lower class, no religion, independent lean Democrat, slightly liberal. In a public goods game with punishment rules: may punish for contributing less than average. So if you contribute less than group average, others can punish you. In period 1, you don't know others' contributions. Typically in such games, rational choice? As a slightly liberal, maybe more cooperative? As lower class, maybe need money? But also want to avoid punishment. Since punishment possible for low contributors, it's risky to contribute low if others contribute higher. Without coordination, one might aim for a moderate contribution. Expected average? If all are similar, maybe contribute something like 5. But with punishment, people may want to avoid being below average; so they may coordinate on high contributions like 5-10. As a lower class, maybe want to keep money, but also avoid punishment which costs 0.25 to punish but reduces someone else by 1. Others may punish low contributors, costing them. So better to contribute enough to not be below average. Since it's period 1, uncertainty. Could guess others will contribute maybe 5. So contribute 5 to match average. That way you can't be punished (exact average is safe). So answer 5.

